name: Washington Office of the Secretary of State
tweet: @pjjaske The media may choose to call the outcome of races before all the ballots have been counted. However, results are not official until certified.   Counties will certify the results on Nov. 24.

name: Washington Office of the Secretary of State
tweet: @SayItEllieB @C2m1ll3 Many counties have set up live streaming feeds to accommodate public viewing during the pandemic. Please contact your election office directly if you would like to find out more about these options:  https://t.co/aRLU2qjh11

name: Washington Office of the Secretary of State
tweet: @SayItEllieB @C2m1ll3 The voting system is tested and certified by the Secretary of State‚Äôs office. Before each election, we conduct Logic and Accuracy (L&A) tests on the counting equipment, and after the election we run audits of the ballots.

name: Washington Office of the Secretary of State
tweet: @SayItEllieB @C2m1ll3 The ballot is then separated from the return envelope and the interior secrecy sleeve or envelope, and is prepared for tabulation. At that point, the ballot cannot be traced back to the voter.

name: Washington Office of the Secretary of State
tweet: @SayItEllieB @C2m1ll3 During ballot processing, county election workers verify the signature on the return envelope matches the signature on file in the voter‚Äôs registration record. Once the signature has been validated, the voter is credited with voting.

name: Washington Office of the Secretary of State
tweet: @SayItEllieB @C2m1ll3 With regard to your second question, The Washington State Constitution requires the absolute secrecy of your vote. No person observing or canvassing an election can determine a voter‚Äôs identity from looking at a voted ballot.

name: Washington Office of the Secretary of State
tweet: @SayItEllieB @C2m1ll3 Prior to every election, counties perform logic and accuracy tests to ensure the accuracy of the vote counting equipment before each election. Additionally, post-election audits are conducted to ensure the system correctly recorded the votes cast.

name: Washington Office of the Secretary of State
tweet: @SayItEllieB @C2m1ll3 Before a system can be certified for use in Washington state, it must be tested by an Election Assistance Commission-accredited, independent testing authority. Then, our independent state Election System Certification Board reviews and recommends acceptance for use within WA.

tweet: @Shelley29632112 The return envelope with the voter‚Äôs name is separated from the ballot permanently once the signature has been verified and the voter has been credited with voting, and ballots do not contain any identifying information linking them to a specific voter.
